four locations around Boston.

00:37:01.490 --> 00:37:03.720
How connected are you to the
communities and the other

00:37:03.720 --> 00:37:06.190
restaurant owners and
bakery owners?

00:37:06.190 --> 00:37:10.340
Do you guys help each other
out and stay in touch?

00:37:10.340 --> 00:37:13.230
JOANNE CHANG: The restaurant and
bakery community in Boston

00:37:13.230 --> 00:37:15.870
and Cambridge is extremely
tight-knit.

00:37:15.870 --> 00:37:17.280
Everybody knows everybody.

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:19.790
Everybody sees everybody at
events and goes to everybody's

00:37:19.790 --> 00:37:21.110
restaurants.

00:37:21.110 --> 00:37:22.670
So yes, we're very connected.

00:37:22.670 --> 00:37:23.850
I feel very connected.

00:37:23.850 --> 00:37:26.710
In fact, we're looking for
a sous-chef position

00:37:26.710 --> 00:37:27.610
at Myers and Chang.

00:37:27.610 --> 00:37:30.490
And I just this morning sent an
email out to all of my chef

00:37:30.490 --> 00:37:32.750
friends just saying, if you know
of anybody, or if there's

00:37:32.750 --> 00:37:35.370
anybody on your team that is
ready to move on and you don't

00:37:35.370 --> 00:37:37.390
need them, send them our way.

00:37:37.390 --> 00:37:38.850
So we all feel very connected.

00:37:38.850 --> 00:37:43.260
I will reach out to Maura at
Sofra on a periodic basis, or

00:37:43.260 --> 00:37:45.820
vice versa, if she needs
something or if I need

00:37:45.820 --> 00:37:48.160
something, her advice.

00:37:48.160 --> 00:37:52.540
The woman who runs Tatte Bakery,
her pastry chef used

00:37:52.540 --> 00:37:54.900
to work for me as my pastry
chef, and so Kristin and I

00:37:54.900 --> 00:37:56.480
stay in touch.

00:37:56.480 --> 00:37:58.970
And then, all the chefs, they
just all know each other.

00:37:58.970 --> 00:38:01.390
We work really well together.

00:38:04.156 --> 00:38:06.300
AUDIENCE: I was just wondering,
I like to test

00:38:06.300 --> 00:38:08.880
around the kitchen as well
quite a bit, but I never

00:38:08.880 --> 00:38:10.110
actually remember the recipes.

00:38:10.110 --> 00:38:12.680
So I didn't know, when you go
into testing a new recipe, do

00:38:12.680 --> 00:38:13.860
you take down the
measurements?

00:38:13.860 --> 00:38:16.248
Or what's your process
for doing that so you

00:38:16.248 --> 00:38:17.215
can remember it again?

00:38:17.215 --> 00:38:19.260
JOANNE CHANG: I definitely
write it down first.

00:38:19.260 --> 00:38:21.800
One of the things I tell people
what I'm doing a demo,

00:38:21.800 --> 00:38:25.590
for example, is you know when
you're watching on Food TV,

00:38:25.590 --> 00:38:27.510
and they have all the little
cups with everything all

00:38:27.510 --> 00:38:28.810
measured out, and they
go, boom, boom,

00:38:28.810 --> 00:38:29.880
boom and it's done?

00:38:29.880 --> 00:38:32.800
That's actually how I bake.

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:34.650
If I'm testing a recipe-- like
right now I'm in the middle of

00:38:34.650 --> 00:38:35.720
this low-sugar thing--

00:38:35.720 --> 00:38:40.010
I write down a recipe that in
my head I think will work.

00:38:40.010 --> 00:38:42.980
And then I go and I measure
everything out, and then I

00:38:42.980 --> 00:38:44.800
have my piece of paper with
a pen next to me.

00:38:44.800 --> 00:38:47.270
And as I'm baking, if I
see an adjustment--

00:38:47.270 --> 00:38:50.290
I'll add a cup of milk and
realize ooh, it needs more

00:38:50.290 --> 00:38:52.290
liquid-- then I'll add it and
I'll measure another quarter,

00:38:52.290 --> 00:38:54.060
and then I'll change
the recipe.

00:38:54.060 --> 00:38:59.400
For me, it's not like cooking.

00:38:59.400 --> 00:39:00.770
If I'm just cooking at home,
I wouldn't think

00:39:00.770 --> 00:39:01.430
so much about it.

00:39:01.430 --> 00:39:03.670
But because I need to replicate
it, I have to be

00:39:03.670 --> 00:39:08.420
really careful about taking
really detailed notes.

00:39:08.420 --> 00:39:11.100
It can be a little bit less fun,
because you're trying to

00:39:11.100 --> 00:39:12.830
just make something delicious,
and then, aw, shoot, I got to

00:39:12.830 --> 00:39:14.170
remember to write this down.

00:39:14.170 --> 00:39:17.170
But I've gotten used to it over
testing these two books

00:39:17.170 --> 00:39:18.140
these past couple years.

00:39:18.140 --> 00:39:21.680
So it's definitely the best
way in order to be able to

00:39:21.680 --> 00:39:22.930
replicate it going forward.

00:39:28.200 --> 00:39:31.520
AUDIENCE: You have a few
successful businesses that

00:39:31.520 --> 00:39:32.150
you've started.

00:39:32.150 --> 00:39:34.700
You've written a couple
of books.

00:39:34.700 --> 00:39:37.610
At this point, you said you
make it into some of your

00:39:37.610 --> 00:39:39.993
businesses some of the time,
depending on what you can fit

00:39:39.993 --> 00:39:41.190
in the schedule.

00:39:41.190 --> 00:39:43.490
So they're obviously sustaining
themselves in ways

00:39:43.490 --> 00:39:46.180
that was not possible
at the beginning.

00:39:46.180 --> 00:39:48.235
How self-sustaining are
your businesses?

00:39:48.235 --> 00:39:51.620
And what's next for you, given
that you've been able to free

00:39:51.620 --> 00:39:52.760
up some of the time
in your schedule?

00:39:52.760 --> 00:39:54.430
JOANNE CHANG: Sure.

00:39:54.430 --> 00:39:57.260
The businesses, at this point,
if I were to just drop off the

00:39:57.260 --> 00:40:01.360
face of the Earth, there's a
couple things that I do that

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:04.850
I'm still the only
one who does.

00:40:04.850 --> 00:40:06.180
But it wouldn't be hard
to teach somebody.

00:40:06.180 --> 00:40:09.060
So for example payroll, which
happens every other week, I

00:40:09.060 --> 00:40:09.910
have an HR person.

00:40:09.910 --> 00:40:11.960
She runs payroll.

00:40:11.960 --> 00:40:14.580
She talks to all the managers to
make sure everybody's time

00:40:14.580 --> 00:40:15.230
clocks are correct.

00:40:15.230 --> 00:40:18.840
But I physically enter it into
our accounting system, because

00:40:18.840 --> 00:40:21.950
I want to see how much we're
paying everybody.

00:40:21.950 --> 00:40:23.260
That's easy enough.

00:40:23.260 --> 00:40:26.430
If I were to move to Tahiti, I
could just teach her how to do

00:40:26.430 --> 00:40:29.840
that part, and she
could do it.

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:32.590
Honestly, I think that's
the only thing

00:40:32.590 --> 00:40:34.590
that I do that I have--

00:40:34.590 --> 00:40:36.550
And I field a lot
of the email.

00:40:36.550 --> 00:40:43.460
We get a lot of emails, either
complaints or requests for

00:40:43.460 --> 00:40:47.150
information or charity
requests.

00:40:47.150 --> 00:40:51.580
And I tend to answer most of
them, especially the complaint

00:40:51.580 --> 00:40:55.100
ones, just because they are
important to me, and I want to

00:40:55.100 --> 00:40:57.610
stay on top of them all.

00:40:57.610 --> 00:41:00.200
But that, again, I could also
easily give that to my

00:41:00.200 --> 00:41:01.770
director of operations,
who would gladly do

00:41:01.770 --> 00:41:03.680
all of that for me.

00:41:03.680 --> 00:41:06.620
I think what would be missing,
and it's one of the reasons

00:41:06.620 --> 00:41:09.370
why I don't want to not be at
the bakeries as much as I can,

00:41:09.370 --> 00:41:12.810
is the connection that I have
with the staff, trying to make

00:41:12.810 --> 00:41:15.210
them understand the
story of Flour.

00:41:15.210 --> 00:41:20.610
And we're at this point where
some people call us a chain.

00:41:20.610 --> 00:41:24.370
And I don't want it ever
to feel like that.

00:41:24.370 --> 00:41:25.720
We were talking earlier
about how Google's

00:41:25.720 --> 00:41:26.610
gotten really big.

00:41:26.610 --> 00:41:29.750
And I'm sure that whoever the
big people are wish it were

00:41:29.750 --> 00:41:30.400
still small.

00:41:30.400 --> 00:41:34.230
And so trying to maintain that
small company atmosphere, even

00:41:34.230 --> 00:41:38.020
though it's gotten bigger, is
something that I think I'm

00:41:38.020 --> 00:41:40.230
uniquely positioned to
do, simply because I

00:41:40.230 --> 00:41:42.300
don't have a job title.

00:41:42.300 --> 00:41:44.830
My executive pastry chef, she's
in charge of pastry, so

00:41:44.830 --> 00:41:47.510
she spends all her time actually
working on pastries.

00:41:47.510 --> 00:41:49.520
And the HR person,
she does HR.

00:41:49.520 --> 00:41:50.880
But for me, I'm just owner.

00:41:50.880 --> 00:41:52.180
So what do I do?

00:41:52.180 --> 00:41:55.590
I try to make sure that the
place that they are working at

00:41:55.590 --> 00:41:58.310
is what I intended it to be.

00:41:58.310 --> 00:42:01.580
Because I think it's very easy,
without guidance, for it

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:04.980
to, like I was saying earlier,
just veer off, and not

00:42:04.980 --> 00:42:08.410
necessarily in a bad way, but
just in a way that's not what

00:42:08.410 --> 00:42:09.630
I intended.

00:42:09.630 --> 00:42:12.660
And so it's not that my way is
the right way, but I think

00:42:12.660 --> 00:42:14.895
there's something to be said
for running a business that

00:42:14.895 --> 00:42:16.520
has a clear vision.

00:42:16.520 --> 00:42:19.970
And if there's not one person or
one group of people that's

00:42:19.970 --> 00:42:23.270
kind of setting the vision on a
daily basis and having that

00:42:23.270 --> 00:42:25.750
be their focus, I think it's
easy for companies

00:42:25.750 --> 00:42:28.802
to lose their way.

00:42:28.802 --> 00:42:30.660
I don't know if that really
answers your question.

00:42:30.660 --> 00:42:35.260
It's not like a specific job
thing that I do conscious--

00:42:35.260 --> 00:42:38.290
I do it consciously, but there's
not a list of things I

00:42:38.290 --> 00:42:38.960
do to do that.

00:42:38.960 --> 00:42:41.080
It's just kind of how I
try to stay connected

00:42:41.080 --> 00:42:42.440
to the various bakeries.

00:42:42.440 --> 00:42:44.150
AUDIENCE: And what's next?

00:42:44.150 --> 00:42:46.115
JOANNE CHANG: Oh,
and what's next?

00:42:46.115 --> 00:42:50.635
Writing the third book, and then
after that the "Myers and

00:42:50.635 --> 00:42:51.635
Chang" book, definitely.

00:42:51.635 --> 00:42:52.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:53.330
JOANNE CHANG: No.

00:42:53.330 --> 00:42:57.290
This time I made Bill, my
publisher, commit to this.

00:42:57.290 --> 00:42:59.800
I said, OK, so I'll do
this one, and then--

00:42:59.800 --> 00:43:01.170
He actually had a good point.

00:43:01.170 --> 00:43:04.045
He said that with the timing of
it, if I do the "Myers and

00:43:04.045 --> 00:43:05.970
Chang" book, it will come out
at Myers and Chang's 10th

00:43:05.970 --> 00:43:09.310
anniversary, which seems to make
sense and works and feels

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:11.380
good and all that.

00:43:11.380 --> 00:43:13.790
And after that, I honestly
don't know.

00:43:17.250 --> 00:43:18.820
Even though I'm talking about
how you have to have a clear

00:43:18.820 --> 00:43:21.190
vision, I haven't had a
clear path about what

00:43:21.190 --> 00:43:22.590
I want to do next.

00:43:22.590 --> 00:43:27.530
I don't want to open more
bakeries, but I feel like I

00:43:27.530 --> 00:43:28.910
have to be careful
when I say that.

00:43:28.910 --> 00:43:31.670
Because I'm pretty sure when I
came here last time, when we

00:43:31.670 --> 00:43:34.660
only had the three bakeries, I
probably said the same thing.

00:43:34.660 --> 00:43:36.250
And yet, we opened a fourth.

00:43:36.250 --> 00:43:39.110
But what's stopping us this time
from opening a fifth is

00:43:39.110 --> 00:43:41.660
that physically we are limited
with how we're doing our

00:43:41.660 --> 00:43:42.230
production.

00:43:42.230 --> 00:43:44.560
If we were to open a fifth,
we would have to build a

00:43:44.560 --> 00:43:47.180
commissary kitchen, which
we don't have now.

00:43:47.180 --> 00:43:52.180
And so, for me, if we were to go
that route, that's a huge,

00:43:52.180 --> 00:43:53.040
big next step.

00:43:53.040 --> 00:43:55.240
That just changes the
business model.

00:43:55.240 --> 00:43:57.790
Because right now, I can still,
in my head, convince

00:43:57.790 --> 00:43:59.760
myself that I just have
four little bakeries.

00:43:59.760 --> 00:44:02.010
But once you go commissary, then
you become commissary.

00:44:04.896 --> 00:44:07.782
You're welcome.

00:44:07.782 --> 00:44:11.149
AUDIENCE: Very interesting
connection with [INAUDIBLE]--

00:44:11.149 --> 00:44:13.710
excuse me-- is how do you
define yourself--

00:44:13.710 --> 00:44:15.260
I didn't come for the beginning,
so I might have

00:44:15.260 --> 00:44:17.730
missed something you said--

00:44:17.730 --> 00:44:19.810
compared to the other bakeries
in the area?

00:44:19.810 --> 00:44:21.510
Iggy's obviously has a different
business model.

00:44:21.510 --> 00:44:21.923
JOANNE CHANG: Sure.

00:44:21.923 --> 00:44:25.125
AUDIENCE: But the product has
a lot of similarities.

00:44:25.125 --> 00:44:29.837
Hi-Rise seems to be focused on
high price, which applies to

00:44:29.837 --> 00:44:32.505
all of you.

00:44:32.505 --> 00:44:33.710
How do you define yourself,
compared

00:44:33.710 --> 00:44:36.810
to the other bakeries?

00:44:36.810 --> 00:44:42.390
JOANNE CHANG: One thing that
we try to do is we try to

00:44:42.390 --> 00:44:45.870
spend a lot of time just staying
focused on what we do

00:44:45.870 --> 00:44:49.490
and not spend a lot of time
looking at what the others do

00:44:49.490 --> 00:44:52.720
and how we relate
vis-a-vis them.

00:44:52.720 --> 00:44:57.380
When I started Flour
13 years ago, it

00:44:57.380 --> 00:44:58.240
was a couple of things.

00:44:58.240 --> 00:45:02.170
It was, from a point of view,
making sure that that was

00:45:02.170 --> 00:45:03.310
always a priority.

00:45:03.310 --> 00:45:05.640
Which it sounds obvious,
you're opening a food

00:45:05.640 --> 00:45:07.260
business, so of course food
should be obvious.

00:45:07.260 --> 00:45:12.630
But it's very easy for a food
business, after a certain

00:45:12.630 --> 00:45:15.560
number of years, to just kind
of go on automatic.

00:45:15.560 --> 00:45:19.170
And so we spend a lot of time
really working on-- even

00:45:19.170 --> 00:45:20.370
though the menu doesn't
change much--

00:45:20.370 --> 00:45:22.980
constantly trying to tweak the
recipes and make them a little

00:45:22.980 --> 00:45:25.440
bit better or figure out how
to do it a little bit

00:45:25.440 --> 00:45:28.570
differently so that we're
interested but the customers

00:45:28.570 --> 00:45:32.500
don't get upset that we've
changed something.

00:45:32.500 --> 00:45:35.760
Then, again, part of my mission
statement 13 years ago

00:45:35.760 --> 00:45:38.980
was trying to create an
environment that, as a

00:45:38.980 --> 00:45:42.120
customer when you walk
in, you feel like--

00:45:42.120 --> 00:45:45.220
it's cheesy, but I always say
it's like "Cheers"-- it's a

00:45:45.220 --> 00:45:46.200
home away from home.

00:45:46.200 --> 00:45:47.880
And that's what I want
Flour to be.

00:45:47.880 --> 00:45:49.480
I want Flour to be a place
where people in the

00:45:49.480 --> 00:45:52.540
neighborhood come to the bakery
and feel like it's

00:45:52.540 --> 00:45:53.320
their place.

00:45:53.320 --> 00:45:56.210
And in the South End,
for example--

00:45:56.210 --> 00:45:57.730
that's the first one--

00:45:57.730 --> 00:46:01.290
we have a ton of regulars
who we know on a

00:46:01.290 --> 00:46:02.670
very personal level.

00:46:02.670 --> 00:46:04.760
And they come in, and
it is their bakery.

00:46:04.760 --> 00:46:06.300
They tell us what to change.

00:46:06.300 --> 00:46:07.535
They clean up for us.

00:46:07.535 --> 00:46:09.840
And it's become a really
nice community.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:12.710
Obviously, people flit in and
flit out, but, for me, that's

00:46:12.710 --> 00:46:13.770
something that--

00:46:13.770 --> 00:46:16.140
I don't even know if it sets us
apart, because I don't know

00:46:16.140 --> 00:46:17.820
what the other bakeries
are trying to do.

00:46:17.820 --> 00:46:21.730
But I think all of the
bakeries around us--

00:46:21.730 --> 00:46:22.810
I love Iggy's.

00:46:22.810 --> 00:46:24.160
But to me, they're wholesale.

00:46:24.160 --> 00:46:25.530
And I know they have the little

00:46:25.530 --> 00:46:26.950
outpost I think on Fawcett--

00:46:26.950 --> 00:46:27.920
AUDIENCE: Every Sunday.

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:28.403
JOANNE CHANG: Oh, really?

00:46:28.403 --> 00:46:28.886
OK.

00:46:28.886 --> 00:46:30.820
AUDIENCE: That's where
I go every Sunday.

00:46:30.820 --> 00:46:31.210
JOANNE CHANG: Oh, OK.

00:46:31.210 --> 00:46:31.440
Yeah.

00:46:31.440 --> 00:46:32.120
I think they're great.

00:46:32.120 --> 00:46:34.270
But they're focusing on
wholesale, which is different.

00:46:34.270 --> 00:46:35.336
AUDIENCE: That's why I said
about the business model.

00:46:35.336 --> 00:46:35.470
Yeah.

00:46:35.470 --> 00:46:41.080
JOANNE CHANG: I think the
closest to us, at this point--

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:45.176
Hi-Rise is very similar
to us, to what we do.

00:46:45.176 --> 00:46:48.400
But he doesn't do the
fancy cakes, and so

00:46:48.400 --> 00:46:50.290
we have that focus.

00:46:50.290 --> 00:46:52.530
And then, Tatte Bakery I feel
like recently has become

00:46:52.530 --> 00:46:54.150
similar to what we do.

00:46:54.150 --> 00:46:57.045
Bread and Butter, which just
opened up in the North End, I

00:46:57.045 --> 00:46:59.300
haven't been yet, but I think
it's similar to what we do.

00:46:59.300 --> 00:47:05.130
I think there's enough people
out there to kind of be able

00:47:05.130 --> 00:47:08.610
to have numerous bakeries and
just each place be a little

00:47:08.610 --> 00:47:11.120
bit different, just based on
their own personalities.

00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:13.090
Again, I'm not trying to define
myself vis-a-vis them.

00:47:13.090 --> 00:47:15.360
I just try to define myself
vis-a-vis what

00:47:15.360 --> 00:47:16.755
I'm trying to do.

00:47:16.755 --> 00:47:19.910
And to the earlier question
about what would happen if I

00:47:19.910 --> 00:47:23.500
were to move or stop being
involved every day, I feel

00:47:23.500 --> 00:47:26.860
like that's what I'm always
doing is just trying to set

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:31.540
the tone of the place and the
spirit, so that when you walk

00:47:31.540 --> 00:47:35.010
in it is clear that it's Flour
and not just one of the

00:47:35.010 --> 00:47:37.270
various bakeries that
you can walk into.

00:47:37.270 --> 00:47:38.190
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:38.190 --> 00:47:38.850
SANDRA LEUNG LI: I think
we have time

00:47:38.850 --> 00:47:40.100
for one more question.

00:47:42.760 --> 00:47:45.320
AUDIENCE: So from the new
cookbook, what one recipe

00:47:45.320 --> 00:47:48.341
would you say, oh, you've
got to try this one?

00:47:48.341 --> 00:47:50.289
JOANNE CHANG: Uhh--

00:47:50.289 --> 00:47:51.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:51.750 --> 00:47:53.000
AUDIENCE: All of them.

00:47:57.360 --> 00:48:00.490
JOANNE CHANG: Well, the book
is divided into breakfast,

00:48:00.490 --> 00:48:03.930
lunch, dinner, party, drinks.

00:48:03.930 --> 00:48:07.050
Give me a category, and
then I'll tell you.

00:48:07.050 --> 00:48:08.050
AUDIENCE: Party.

00:48:08.050 --> 00:48:08.300
JOANNE CHANG: OK.

00:48:08.300 --> 00:48:11.910
Party time, I would say--

00:48:11.910 --> 00:48:12.100
OK.

00:48:12.100 --> 00:48:14.350
This isn't my answer, but I'm
just going to throw it out

00:48:14.350 --> 00:48:15.650
there, because we
have samples.

00:48:15.650 --> 00:48:19.870
The Spectacular Spice Pecans,
which don't look like much and

00:48:19.870 --> 00:48:22.760
aren't like a sexy treat to
bring to an event like this,

00:48:22.760 --> 00:48:25.570
the reason why we brought them
is that we did a book launch

00:48:25.570 --> 00:48:29.150
party with this a couple weeks
ago and had this open house

00:48:29.150 --> 00:48:33.370
with snacks from the book, and
the spiced pecans are the one

00:48:33.370 --> 00:48:35.970
thing that everyone wrote about
and said to me, oh my

00:48:35.970 --> 00:48:37.240
god, I love this.

00:48:37.240 --> 00:48:39.920
But if you were to make
one thing from

00:48:39.920 --> 00:48:45.740
that, I would say either--

00:48:45.740 --> 00:48:48.610
I know I'm hedging here-- either
the Pithivier or the

00:48:48.610 --> 00:48:52.360
Croquembouche, simply because
I think they're both really

00:48:52.360 --> 00:48:55.620
dramatic and really beautiful.

00:48:55.620 --> 00:48:56.890
They're both delicious.

00:48:56.890 --> 00:49:00.700
And I think they're the type of
dessert that if you want a

00:49:00.700 --> 00:49:02.690
project and you want to do
something that's going to

00:49:02.690 --> 00:49:06.400
impress, I think those two
would do the trick.

00:49:06.400 --> 00:49:10.280
They're both desserts that we
only offer at Christmastime,

00:49:10.280 --> 00:49:14.130
and I spent a lot of time
working on the recipe to make

00:49:14.130 --> 00:49:15.180
it accessible to people.

00:49:15.180 --> 00:49:16.430
So they are a little bit long.

00:49:16.430 --> 00:49:20.240
But if you follow the recipe
step by step, you'll get this

00:49:20.240 --> 00:49:22.670
glorious dessert that you can
present of friends, and it's

00:49:22.670 --> 00:49:24.745
pretty impressive.

00:49:24.745 --> 00:49:25.220
You're welcome.

00:49:25.220 --> 00:49:26.380
SANDRA LEUNG LI: Thank
you very much,

00:49:26.380 --> 00:49:27.580
Joanne, for coming today.

00:49:27.580 --> 00:49:28.180
JOANNE CHANG: Thank
you so much.

00:49:28.180 --> 00:49:31.317
[APPLAUSE]

